- Silicon wafers: 4" P-type <100>, 1-10 Ω·cm, prime grade (University Wafer surplus, $15/wafer)
- Boron spin-on dopant: Filmtronics B-153, 500mL ($200)
- Phosphorus spin-on dopant: Filmtronics P-8545, 500mL ($200)
- Contact metal: 99.99% aluminum wire for thermal evaporation ($50)
- Tube furnace: SentroTech STF-1200 or homebuilt equivalent ($800-1500)
- Mask aligner: Homebuilt UV-LED exposure system on linear stage ($400)
- Photoresist: AZ 1512 or SU-8 depending on feature size ($100)
- Wire bonder: Manual ball bonder or conductive epoxy alternative ($500 vs $50)



The Scaling Principle

The physics doesn't care about absolute size — it cares about ratios. If you scale the device up by 100× in XY, you need to scale voltages, doping densities, and thermal gradients accordingly. The octahedral encoding is a topological structure — the vertex relationships survive scaling as long as the ratios between n, d, ℓ, and κ are preserved.

What this means for a buildable version:

· Device area: 1 mm² instead of 1 µm²
· Feature size: 5 µm instead of 50 nm
· Coil diameter: 100 µm instead of 100 nm
· Contacts: wire-bonded instead of nano-vias
· Readout: oscilloscope instead of lock-in at THz

The computational phase space (purity × entanglement) is scale-invariant. You'll hit the same vertices at different absolute values of n and d. The sim can be recalibrated for the scaled device.


Stage 1: Substrate Prep (start with finished wafers, skip ingot)

· Clean wafers in piranha etch (H₂SO₄:H₂O₂, 3:1) — do this outside, in PPE, with a fan
· HF dip to remove native oxide — 2% HF, 30 seconds, DI water rinse
· Spin dry on a 3D-printed spinner (brushless motor + chuck)

Stage 2: Doping (spin-on + furnace drive, replaces implanter)

· Spin dopant film at 3000 RPM for 30 seconds
· Soft bake at 200°C for 15 minutes (hot plate)
· Drive-in at 1000°C for 1-4 hours in tube furnace with N₂ flow
· Strip oxide in HF, measure sheet resistance with 4-point probe

Stage 3: Patterning (shadow mask or contact lithography)

· Apply photoresist, expose through printed mask on transparency film
· Develop, etch, strip
· Repeat for each layer (doping, contacts, coils)

Stage 4: Contact Deposition (thermal evaporation)

· Homebuilt evaporator: bell jar + diffusion pump + tungsten boat
· Deposit aluminum pads through shadow mask
· Anneal contacts at 400°C for 30 minutes in forming gas

Stage 5: Coil Formation (electroplating through mask)

· Seed layer deposition (sputter or evaporate thin copper)
· Pattern coil in thick photoresist (SU-8)
· Electroplate copper into mold
· Strip resist, etch seed layer

Stage 6: Encapsulation (spin-on glass or silicone)

· Spin coat protective layer
· Open contact windows via lithography or mechanical probing

Stage 7: Test and Calibrate

· Probe station: XYZ micromanipulators + microscope ($500)
· Source-measure unit: Keithley 2400 on eBay or homebuilt Arduino SMU ($300-800)
· Oscilloscope for transient response
· Temperature control: Peltier stage + thermocouple + PID controller ($200)

3. Vertex Calibration Procedure

This is the bridge from sim to physical operation:

Step 1: Establish S0

· Apply nominal biases. Measure I-V curve. Compare to sim prediction for default n, d.
· If current is too high: n is above spec. Reduce drive-in time.
· If current is too low: d is too high. Re-anneal to reduce defects.

Step 2: Locate the 8 vertices

· Sweep control voltages (gate, substrate bias, pump LED)
· At each setting, measure the 6 observables that map to your S-vector
· Compute vertex weights in real-time (microcontroller running your Python weight calculation or a simplified lookup table)
· Identify the voltage setpoints that maximize weight for each of the 8 vertices
· Record these as VERTEX_VOLTAGES[0] through VERTEX_VOLTAGES[7]

Step 3: Map the computational phase space

· Steer from vertex to vertex, recording purity and entanglement at each step
· Verify the diagonal vertices host separable/solitonic computation (low off-diagonal kernel response)
· Verify the axis vertices host entangled/nonlocal computation (high spatial correlation between contacts)
· Locate Ω² ≈ 0 by finding the bias condition where signal becomes maximally sensitive to small perturbations

Step 4: Tune feedback loop

· Set PID gains for vertex steering based on measured response times
· Verify the device can hold a vertex against drift for > 1 minute (minimum for computation)
· Characterize noise floor — this sets your error rate

The Single Most Important Calibration

The Ω² sign transition is your only hard boundary. Everything else is continuous. In the physical device, Ω² is measured as:

Ω² > 0: Device is in normal operating regime. Signal propagates, output is predictable.
Ω² = 0: Device is at maximum sensitivity. Small input → large output. This is your readout point.
Ω² < 0: Device is in unstable regime. Oscillation or latch-up possible. Avoid for steady computation, useful for reset.

Finding this boundary physically: Sweep substrate bias while measuring gain. The point where gain spikes (diverging sensitivity) is Ω² ≈ 0. Mark this voltage. Stay 10-20% away from it except during intentional readout.


